##Wuhan Emergency first-line Doctors Dictation: I wish winter passed earlier

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

In March 2019, Sun Peng, deputy director of the Emergency Department at Wuhan Union Hospital, was transferred to the hospital's West Wing to take charge of the emergency department. At the end of December, after the coronavirus outbreak in the south China Seafood Market, he opened a fever clinic in the West Hospital, and the work of both clinics fell to him. On the morning of January 26, Sun Peng told reporters that the hospital had just been notified that its Western hospital had also been designated as a designated hospital, becoming one of the third batch of hospitals in Wuhan to admit and treat patients diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia.
Here's what Sun Peng said.

Dictation | Sun Peng

Reporter

The most exhausting New Year's Eve

Ten days ago, I packed some clothes from home, moved into a House I rented near the hospital, and began isolating myself. New Year's Eve at 9 o'clock, I just arrived at the residence, want to say the new year, a person also cooking dumplings. Just finished eating, and rushed to the hospital, because a patient suddenly deteriorated.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The patient, who had just been diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia this morning, had not yet been taken to a designated hospital. In the morning I asked him how he was feeling, he said "pretty good" , the whole day is actually good, but at night and then took a sharp turn down.

We saved for over an hour, wearing protective masks, masks, wearing protective clothing, we actually know, so close to the rescue, infection rate increased many, but this time doctors can not retreat, will not retreat. I was hoping for a miracle, but the patient wasn't doing well, and pneumonia was a severe blow to an old man with common heart and blood pressure problems. In fact, at present our hospital's death case also by the old, has the basic disease patient majority.

He had a very rapid progression that night, and there had been one rescue, and it worked, and this second time, sadly, it didn't. We put him in a body bag and put him in a hearse. Normally, when a patient is declared dead, the rest of the work is done by the family and the funeral home, but at times like this, the family has panic attacks, and that's pretty much what we do. There was another death that night, another very old patient, who had been bedridden for a long time. The family decided not to have active intubation and naturally left that night.

When it was over, it was early in the morning, and I was driving home from the hospital. Maybe it was dark, maybe there was no public transportation, maybe there was fog on my glasses, and I didn't see a single car on the road. Driving alone on a road like this, I had a few images in my head. It has been raining all the time in Wuhan. It is cold and Wet. I am standing in the middle of the ward with two dead bodies beside me. My colleagues pass by wearing protective clothing. I am also wearing protective clothing. I am wearing goggles. My glasses are still in my goggles. It is foggy every day, there are patients lining up, hearing their families crying outside the door.

Then I sent a message to the group of colleagues, "the rescue of a night, the last two bodies to end, it is really tired. ". I've been doing this for over 20 years, and it's not uncommon for me to spend New Year's Eve in the emergency department. But from 30 years ago in the ward, there are some New Year's atmosphere, last night is not really. After saving the patient, I was exhausted. This feeling of helplessness is not good, the last day of the year, really sad.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Author: Zhang Xueyan, "homage to medical staff"

This month, I always carry a heart, the most worried about is colleagues in the fall. A few days ago, Dr. Queena Chan of our department told me after working the night shift that he had a fever. My heart was "clucking" at that time, and I could feel that she was also very nervous. After working the night shift, people were at their weakest, i quickly arranged for her to do tests, praying that she was just a common cold. The young woman doctor, after only one day's rest, sent me a message saying, "chief, if I don't have a fever at night, I'll go to work tomorrow, so that my colleagues don't take over and tire them out. ". My nose is sore from hearing that. Fortunately, her coronavirus nucleic acid test came back negative.

I've got three doctors on the crash cart, 24 hours, two days off, three shifts. To be honest, it's a tough job because they're mostly transporting patients now. The journey can be as short as an hour and as long as more than two hours, in a confined space, at close quarters with the critically ill, some with suction machines. Their isolation clothes are not breathable, the carriage is stuffy, run underwear on a wet, come back to the car disinfection, a change of clothes, and then send the next, the latest time until four or five o'clock in the morning. How stressed do you think they are? But no one told me anything.

Fever clinic has a rotation, a few days, there will be a group of colleagues to replace us, only down, we can safely retreat together.

I wish winter would go away

We had 20 observation beds at the fever clinic in the West Wing, and we didn't expect this many patients. At the end of December, I remember, we started with just one or two patients from the south China Seafood Market. At first, it said "no one passed on" . Later, the judgment changed and it said "limited people passed on" . When I reached more than 100 patients, I made a mark in my heart, and these days it's up to more than 300. There are cross-district visits, because our West Hospital is in Hanyang District, an economic development zone, and there are too many people in the downtown area. Some patients prefer to go far away and cross-district visits; others come for follow-up visits, so that, it's just snowballing. It's snowballing.

In contrast to the growing number of people, patients are more emotionally stable than usual. Our nurses are also saying that in the past, when we went to the doctor, sometimes we waited in line for a long time, and there would be patients who would lose their temper and make a lot of noise with the medical staff, this time it was much quieter. I think there are three reasons: first, people are becoming aware of the disease; second, they are more or less expecting it when they hear about the cases of friends and relatives around them; and third, the disease is more likely to cause harm to elderly patients, many young patients are able to walk and move freely after infection, which is not the same as being bedridden.

There was a man in his forty that struck me. He brought his father to see a doctor, his father was just a little chest tightness, a little asthma, a little fever, but I looked at the CT film, is a "great white lung. ". I told him it was "not good, " but he thought his father could walk and talk and was clear-headed, and I might be exaggerating. It was early January, and then it got worse, and he was intubated here and transferred to the respiratory intensive care unit. Just down the hall from the Transfer Room, and I don't see him saying a word.

His father didn't make it. A week later, I saw him again, this time on his own. I looked at his scans, and both of his lungs got infected, and then his sister came in, and it was the same thing. You See, the family had three infections.

My second confirmed case of COVID-19 pneumonia was a seafood buyer for the hotel who visited the south China seafood market almost daily. I am very impressed, our negative pressure ambulance to transfer him to the Golden Pool Hospital, his wife was very happy, ran to say thank you, and said "when the condition improved, to take a few native chicken. ". A week later, the fever clinic ran into her again, with a cough, but no fever, but a CT scan of her lungs also showed viral lung, most likely an infection she contracted while caring for a patient, and she was later transferred to the Golden Pool Hospital. It was a very heavy feeling.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Stranger delivered food to Sun Peng's hospital, with a note that read: Delivery boy, please take it to the hospital doctors or nurses, please, you also pay attention to wear protective masks, thank you!

I saw another patient's family today. Her wife is the third pneumonia I've had. The patient had attended an old people's Party and had not been to the south China seafood market. Then he recovered well, and after half a month, I saw his wife again in the hospital, and she saw me and said, thank you. My wife is well, and I am well again.

And what we found was, we had a patient in the ward, and we finally got him out of the hospital, and we were taking care of his family, and after the incubation period, we had another problem. As I began to see more and more patients with family clustering, I felt it was serious. I talked to my colleagues at other hospitals, and they felt the same way. One by one we began to isolate ourselves.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I'm worried about my 14-year-old daughter. My wife is a anesthesiologist at Wuhan Union Hospital Headquarters. Now hospitals are mostly canceled vacation, all staff into the scheduling system, the last two days she told me, soon their turn on the line. As a result, she had to be isolated, leaving her children alone, and the school was delayed. The real question was what to do about food. It feels like, oh, the challenge is still ahead.

A few days ago my daughter wrote me a letter, or classical Chinese style, letter she expressed concern, "the flu suddenly, pneumonia to force, want to father well-being. ". Self-examination, said she blamed me "often early and late, I have broken faith" , meaning that in the future will be more considerate of her father, will not "blame me. It took me by surprise that a child could write such a thing, and I suddenly realized how grown up it was not to have seen my daughter for more than a week, so I consoled my wife by saying, children have to grow up sometime, so I thought I'd take advantage of this moment.

A letter from my daughter

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The letter also said, "I firmly believe that there is no one winter is insurmountable, the current virus raging, as well. ". I often ponder this sentence in my mind, "No winter is insurmountable" , how well said. In these extraordinary times, I see many patients in our observation ward cured, very happy to go home, but can not breathe easy, because patients keep showing up. And then I see my co-workers falling down, going to therapy, stress, worry, fear. I have it all. Often walk in the river, which is not wet shoes, every day bubble in here, maybe one day you slip up, he was hit. But for this team, there's no turning back. You just have to move forward, and you have to watch yourself every time you go to work. I hope winter will be over soon and the day of the Passover will come soon.
